Autonomous Technical Support Robotics

Mathematical Foundations and Architectural Design of the E4 Assistant Robot — Version 4 (Theoretical Edition)

Author: Ouadi Maakoul
Field: Robotics / Artificial Intelligence / Intelligent Systems

---

Abstract

This dissertation presents the mathematical and architectural foundations of E4 Tech‑Support, a humanoid autonomous service robot whose cognitive architecture is designed to satisfy the six axioms of Operationally Stable Intelligence (OSI) as defined by the Fractal Capsule Intelligence (FCI) framework. The central contribution is a fully specified theoretical system: every layer of E4’s intelligence, from sensor fusion to meta‑cognitive self‑modeling, is defined by rigorous mathematical formalisms. The cognitive layer is organized as a four‑nucleus Specialized Agent Orchestration Architecture (SAOA) with Hamiltonian‑inspired coupling dynamics. We prove that under explicitly stated parameter conditions (including small‑gain bounds for inter‑layer coupling and a discrete Lyapunov decrement for the consensus algorithm) the system converges to a unique fixed point and satisfies the FCI contraction and fixed‑point axioms. The diagnostic nucleus implements a symbolic‑neural hybrid with hysteresis‑controlled structural plasticity; we provide finite‑sample concentration bounds for pattern acquisition using martingale inequalities. The self‑diagnostic framework is analyzed using Markov chain large‑deviation bounds to quantify false‑alarm probabilities. The Fractal Intelligence Quotient (FIQ) is operationalized as a geometric mean of four components, where the representational richness component is linked to Rademacher complexity, yielding a rigorous generalization bound. All theoretical claims are supported by mathematical analysis, establishing necessary and sufficient conditions for stability and adaptability under physically realizable parameter regimes.

