Chapter 2: Background and Related Work

2.1 Mathematical Frameworks for Intelligent Systems

Banach fixed‑point theory (Banach, 1922) provides the foundation for contraction mappings in cognitive architectures. Lyapunov stability theory underpins convergence analysis for dynamical systems. Information geometry (Amari, 2016) supplies the tools for analyzing belief manifolds in neural representations. Renormalization group theory (Wilson, 1975) motivates self‑similarity across scales. These foundations are invoked throughout.

2.2 Prior Architectures: Limitations in Formal Grounding

Rule‑based expert systems (Davis et al., 1977) lack formal guarantees beyond their rule sets. Bayesian networks (Pearl, 1988) provide probabilistic semantics but no structural adaptation. Deep learning architectures (LeCun et al., 2015) lack provable stability bounds. Multi‑agent systems (Wooldridge, 2009) typically lack inter‑agent convergence guarantees. The E4 architecture addresses each limitation through its design.

2.3 Fractal Capsule Intelligence: A Proposed Axiomatic Framework

FCI (Maakoul, 2025) proposes six necessary and jointly sufficient conditions for OSI:

· Axiom 1 (Hierarchical Representation) — multi‑scale representation with part‑whole relationships.
· Axiom 2 (Recursive Transformation) — operators that contract uncertainty.
· Axiom 3 (Self‑Similarity) — same computational motif recurs across scales.
· Axiom 4 (Contraction Stability) — composite representation operator is a contraction.
· Axiom 5 (Fixed‑Point Closure) — convergence to a unique fixed point per input.
· Axiom 6 (Meta‑Recursion) — model of its own operation.

We treat FCI as a set of sufficient design principles. The Compliance Regime (spectral normalization, timescale separation, convergent routing) provides a template for satisfying these axioms. This dissertation proves that E4, under specified parameters, satisfies the Compliance Regime and thereby instantiates the FCI principles.

