Chapter 4: Perception and Sensor Fusion — Mathematical Specification

4.1 Sensor Model and Observation Space

Five modalities: RGB images, LiDAR point clouds, thermal images, acoustic time series, proximity readings. Joint observation space $\mathcal{Z} = \times_{i=1}^5 \mathcal{Z}_i$.

4.2 Data Association as Combinatorial Optimization

JCBB (Neira & Tardós, 2001) selects the maximum likelihood consistent hypothesis under Gaussian noise. This is a standard method; we adopt it without modification.

4.3 Extended Kalman Filter for Sensor Fusion

State estimate $\hat{x}_{t|t} \in \mathbb{R}^{13}$ updated via EKF. Prediction and update steps are standard.

Proposition 4.1 (Uncertainty Contraction in the Filter): Under the EKF update, $\operatorname{tr}(P_{t|t}) \le \operatorname{tr}(P_{t|t-1})$, with equality only if $K_t=0$.

Proof: $P_{t|t} = P_{t|t-1} - K_t H_t P_{t|t-1}$, and $K_t H_t P_{t|t-1}$ is positive semidefinite. $\blacksquare$

This contraction property instantiates FCI Axiom 2 for the fusion layer, though process noise $Q_t$ prevents indefinite contraction in practice.

