Chapter 8: Manipulation and Control — Contraction Analysis

8.1 Kinematics and Inverse Kinematics

Standard forward kinematics and damped least‑squares inverse kinematics.

8.2 Joint‑Level Control

PID control: $u(t) = K_p e(t) + K_i \int_0^t e(\tau)d\tau + K_d \dot{e}(t)$. Robot dynamics: $M(q)\ddot{q} + C(q,\dot{q})\dot{q} + g(q) = u(t)$.

Theorem 8.1 (Global Asymptotic Stability of PID Control): For the robot dynamics with gravity compensation, the PID controller with $K_p, K_i, K_d > 0$ renders the closed‑loop system globally asymptotically stable at the desired setpoint.

Proof (energy‑shaping): Define the Lyapunov function

V = \frac12 \dot{q}^T M(q)\dot{q} + \frac12 e^T K_p e + \frac12 \left(\int_0^t e\right)^T K_i \left(\int_0^t e\right) + e^T M(q)\dot{q}.

Using the passivity property and the fact that $\dot{M} - 2C$ is skew‑symmetric, one shows $\dot{V} = -e^T K_d e \le 0$. LaSalle’s invariance principle yields convergence to the largest invariant set where $e=0$ and $\dot{q}=0$, which is the desired equilibrium. The cross term ensures $V$ is positive definite for sufficiently small $K_p$. This is a standard result in robot control [2]. $\blacksquare$

8.3 Grasp Planning

Quality metric $Q(g,O) = P(\text{success}) \cdot \text{FC}(g)$ with force‑closure condition. For precision tasks, augment with alignment score.

