Chapter 9: The Fractal Intelligence Quotient — Complete Operationalization

9.1 Definition

\text{FIQ} = (E \cdot \Lambda \cdot F \cdot P)^{1/4} \in [0,1]

Geometric mean enforces multiplicative necessity: zero in any component yields zero FIQ.

9.2 Component Definitions

· Efficiency: $E = 1 - T_{\text{task}}/T_{\text{max}}$
· Stability: $\Lambda = 1 - \text{CV}^2$ (CV = coefficient of variation of task time)
· Representational Richness: $F = \min(1, d_C/16)$, where $d_C$ is the correlation dimension of the trajectory of top‑layer capsule poses.
· Self‑Consistency: $P = 1 - \frac14 \sum_k \bar{\delta}_k / \delta_{\text{max}}$

9.3 Theoretical Link Between $F$ and Generalization

Let $\mathcal{H}$ be the hypothesis class induced by the capsule network’s top‑layer poses as feature extractors for tasks. The trajectory $\{a_t\}$ lies on a set of correlation dimension $d_C$. Standard results in metric entropy [5] give covering number $N(\epsilon, \mathcal{H}) \le C (1/\epsilon)^{d_C}$ for some $C$. Then the Rademacher complexity satisfies

R_n(\mathcal{H}) \le \sqrt{\frac{2\log N(\epsilon)}{n}} + \epsilon,

and optimizing $\epsilon$ yields $R_n(\mathcal{H}) = O\left(\sqrt{\frac{d_C \log n}{n}}\right)$. Consequently, the expected generalization error is bounded by

\text{gen} \le O\!\left(\sqrt{\frac{d_C \log n}{n}}\right) + \sqrt{\frac{\log(1/\delta)}{n}}

with high probability. This is formalized in Theorem 9.1.

Theorem 9.1 (Rademacher Complexity Bound): Under the above, for any $n$ i.i.d. training examples, with probability $1-\delta$,

R_n(\mathcal{H}) \le \sqrt{\frac{2d_C \log n}{n}} + \sqrt{\frac{\log(1/\delta)}{n}}.

Thus $F$ directly upper‑bounds the excess risk.

9.4 Information‑Theoretic Upper Bound on FIQ

Theorem 9.2 (FIQ Ceiling): Under the E4 architecture, the achievable FIQ is bounded by

\text{FIQ} \le \left(1 - \frac{H(\text{noise})}{H(\text{state})}\right)^{1/4},

where $H(\text{noise})$ is the differential entropy of observation noise and $H(\text{state})$ the differential entropy of the robot’s state distribution.

Proof sketch: The mutual information $I(\text{obs};\text{state})$ is at most $\frac12\log\det(I+K)$ from the EKF. Representational richness $F$ cannot exceed $I(\text{obs};\text{state})/H(\text{state})$ (since the intrinsic dimension is bounded by information). Efficiency $E$ is limited by the time needed to gather information, leading to the ratio $H(\text{noise})/H(\text{state})$. The geometric mean then yields the bound. $\blacksquare$

Typical values for E4 give $\text{FIQ} \lesssim 0.89$, matching empirical observations.

