Appendix A: Mathematical Background and Definitions

A.1 Banach Fixed‑Point Theorem and Contraction Mappings

Let (X,d) be a complete metric space. A mapping T: X \to X is a contraction if there exists \kappa \in [0,1) such that for all x,y \in X,

d(Tx, Ty) \le \kappa \, d(x,y).

Theorem A.1 (Banach Fixed‑Point Theorem). Every contraction T on a complete metric space has a unique fixed point x^* \in X, and for any initial x_0 \in X, the iterates x_{n+1}=Tx_n converge to x^* with geometric rate: d(x_n, x^*) \le \kappa^n d(x_0, x^*).

For product spaces X = X_1 \times \cdots \times X_n with metric d(x,y) = \sum_{i=1}^n d_i(x_i, y_i) (or any equivalent norm), the composition of contractions is a contraction if the contraction factors satisfy a small‑gain condition.

A.2 Lyapunov Stability and LaSalle’s Invariance Principle

Consider a dynamical system \dot{x} = f(x). A function V: \mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R} is a Lyapunov function if V(x) \ge 0, V(x)=0 only at an equilibrium, and \dot{V}(x) = \nabla V(x)^T f(x) \le 0 for all x. If \dot{V}(x) < 0 for all x \neq 0, the equilibrium is globally asymptotically stable.

LaSalle’s Invariance Principle: If \dot{V}(x) \le 0 and the set \{x : \dot{V}(x)=0\} contains no complete trajectories other than the equilibrium, then all trajectories converge to the equilibrium.

For discrete‑time systems x_{t+1} = F(x_t), a Lyapunov function satisfies V(x_{t+1}) - V(x_t) \le -\varphi(\|x_t\|) with \varphi positive definite, implying convergence.

A.3 Jensen‑Shannon Divergence

For probability distributions P and Q over a finite or continuous space, the Jensen‑Shannon divergence is

D_{\text{JS}}(P\|Q) = \frac12 D_{\text{KL}}\!\left(P \middle\| \frac{P+Q}{2}\right) + \frac12 D_{\text{KL}}\!\left(Q \middle\| \frac{P+Q}{2}\right).

Properties: Symmetric, bounded 0 \le D_{\text{JS}} \le \log 2 (for discrete), and jointly convex in (P,Q). Strict convexity holds when P \neq Q.

A.4 Spectral Normalization

For a matrix W, the spectral norm \|W\|_2 = \sigma_{\max}(W) is the largest singular value. Spectral normalization replaces W by \tilde{W} = W / (\|W\|_2 + \epsilon) to enforce \|\tilde{W}\|_2 \le 1. This bounds the Lipschitz constant of the linear layer and is a necessary condition for contraction in neural networks.

A.5 Martingale and Concentration Inequalities

Let \{X_t\}_{t=1}^n be a martingale difference sequence with respect to a filtration \mathcal{F}_t: \mathbb{E}[X_t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-1}] = 0 and |X_t| \le c_t almost surely.

Azuma‑Hoeffding Inequality: For any \epsilon > 0,

\mathbb{P}\left(\left|\sum_{t=1}^n X_t\right| \ge \epsilon\right) \le 2 \exp\left(-\frac{\epsilon^2}{2\sum_{t=1}^n c_t^2}\right).

McDiarmid’s Inequality: If f(x_1,\dots,x_n) has bounded differences |f(x_1,\dots,x_i,\dots,x_n)-f(x_1,\dots,x_i',\dots,x_n)| \le c_i, then

\mathbb{P}\left(|f - \mathbb{E}f| \ge \epsilon\right) \le 2 \exp\left(-\frac{2\epsilon^2}{\sum_{i=1}^n c_i^2}\right).

A.6 Markov Chain Mixing and Spectral Gap

For a finite Markov chain with transition matrix P and stationary distribution \pi, the spectral gap is 1 - \lambda_2, where \lambda_2 is the second largest eigenvalue (in magnitude). The mixing time t_{\text{mix}} satisfies \lambda_2 \le 1 - 1/t_{\text{mix}}. The probability of a run of length m staying in a subset A is bounded by \sup_{x\in A} P_x(\tau_A \ge m) \le \rho^{m-1} where \rho = \max_{x\in A} \mathbb{P}_x(\text{stay in } A) (often related to \lambda_2).

A.7 Rademacher Complexity and Covering Numbers

For a class of functions \mathcal{H} mapping from input space to \mathbb{R}, the empirical Rademacher complexity is

\hat{R}_n(\mathcal{H}) = \mathbb{E}_{\sigma}\left[\sup_{h\in \mathcal{H}} \frac1n \sum_{i=1}^n \sigma_i h(x_i)\right],

where \sigma_i are i.i.d. Rademacher random variables. The covering number N(\epsilon, \mathcal{H}, \|\cdot\|_\infty) is the smallest number of \epsilon-balls needed to cover \mathcal{H}. A standard bound is

\hat{R}_n(\mathcal{H}) \le \inf_{\epsilon > 0} \left\{ \epsilon + \sqrt{\frac{2\log N(\epsilon, \mathcal{H})}{n}} \right\}.

If \log N(\epsilon, \mathcal{H}) \le C d \log(1/\epsilon), then \hat{R}_n(\mathcal{H}) = O(\sqrt{d\log n / n}).

