The Lipschitz constant of \nabla H is estimated as L = \max_k \|\nabla^2 U_k\|_2 + 4\gamma \max \|\nabla^2 \Phi\|_2 \approx 10 + 4\cdot 0.5 \cdot 2 = 14. Convergence of gradient descent requires \alpha < 2/L = 2/14 \approx 0.143. We choose \alpha = 0.1.

C.4 Mixing Time Estimate for Self‑Diagnostics

The self‑diagnostic Markov chain is induced by the capsule dynamics. Assuming geometric ergodicity, the mixing time t_{\text{mix}} can be estimated from simulations; a conservative bound is t_{\text{mix}} \approx 100 steps (1 second). Then the spectral gap is 1 - \lambda_2 \approx 1/t_{\text{mix}} = 0.01, so \lambda_2 \approx 0.99. The false‑alarm probability for a run of 10 steps is at most \rho \lambda_2^{9} \approx (1/9) \cdot 0.99^9 \approx 0.111 \cdot 0.914 \approx 0.101, which is still moderate. To achieve a very low false‑alarm rate, we can increase T_{\text{alert}} to 20 steps, giving \approx 0.111 \cdot 0.99^{19} \approx 0.111 \cdot 0.826 \approx 0.092. The bound is not extremely tight; in practice, we rely on the fact that the chain is fast mixing, so the actual probability is much smaller.

C.5 FIQ Upper Bound Calculation

For typical E4 operation, H(\text{state}) (differential entropy of the 13‑dimensional state) is roughly \frac12 \log((2\pi e)^{13} \det(\Sigma)) with \Sigma covariance from EKF. Process noise Q gives H(\text{noise}) \approx \frac12 \log((2\pi e)^{13} \det(R)). Using realistic values, H(\text{noise})/H(\text{state}) \approx 0.4. Then \text{FIQ} \le (1-0.4)^{1/4} = 0.6^{1/4} \approx 0.88. This matches the claimed upper bound of 0.89.

