Appendix D: Hamiltonian System Equivalence and Delay Analysis

D.1 Symplectic Euler Discretization

The continuous damped Hamiltonian system is

\dot{q}_k = p_k, \qquad \dot{p}_k = -\nabla_{q_k} H - \beta p_k.

Applying the symplectic Euler method with step \alpha:

q_k(t+\alpha) = q_k(t) + \alpha p_k(t+\alpha), \qquad p_k(t+\alpha) = p_k(t) + \alpha (-\nabla_{q_k} H(q(t), p(t)) - \beta p_k(t)).

This yields an implicit scheme. However, Algorithm 1 uses an explicit version:

q_k(t+1) = q_k(t) - \alpha \nabla_{q_k} H(q(t), p(t)) - \beta p_k(t), \quad p_k(t+1) = p_k(t) - \alpha \nabla_{q_k} H(q(t), p(t)).

This is equivalent to a forward Euler discretization of the velocity term. The local truncation error is O(\alpha^2) for both methods.

D.2 Delay Robustness via Razumikhin‑Type Argument

Assume communication delays \tau_d (in steps) such that each nucleus receives outdated information from others. The delayed update is

q_k(t+1) = q_k(t) - \alpha \nabla_{q_k} U_k(q_k(t)) - \gamma \alpha \sum_{j\neq k} \nabla_{q_k} D_{\text{JS}}(P_j(t-\tau_d), P_k(t)) - \beta p_k(t).

Define the Lyapunov function V(t) = H(q(t), p(t)). Using a Razumikhin condition, if \tau_d is small enough, we can show V(t+1) - V(t) \le -\frac{\alpha\beta}{2} \sum \|p_k(t)\|^2 for sufficiently large t. The proof follows by expanding V(t+1) and bounding the effect of the delayed gradient using the fact that \|\nabla H\| is Lipschitz and the state differences over \tau_d steps are bounded by O(\alpha \tau_d). The sufficient condition \tau_d < 1/\beta emerges from a small‑gain inequality.

